{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Mapping Literacy\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0  Lesson Plan\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Class learning objectives\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Students will become familiar with web maps as a scholarly resource and will be able to read them critically. They will learn the grammar common to maps.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Connection to course learning objectives\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Before students can create maps they need to understand what kinds of maps are worth creating. This lesson aims to create student interest in mapping.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Before class: student tasks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Identify one map (perhaps excluding Google Maps, Bing Maps, MapQuest, etc.) that the student has used in the past month.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Before class: instructor tasks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Identify a handful of maps, preferably some within and some outside of the course content. These amps should contain some positive and some negative examples.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Hook\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Option 1: Ask several students to demo the maps that they have brought to class. (Or, this could be part of the interaction/practice.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Option 2: Demonstrate a scholarly map which illustrates themes in the course content.\par}
