{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Demo/Introduction\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Depending on the map chosen, ask students to identify its key features.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab What argument does this map make?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab How does it communicate its argument?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab What do you have to know in advance to understand this map?\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Interaction/practice\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In small groups, students will explore at least two interactive maps. They will try to answer the same questions as above.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Points to get across\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Maps work by aligning multiple sources of information to a spatial grid.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Maps are a representation of reality not the reality itself.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Maps are powerfully persuasive, but must be read critically.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Depending on which map is chosen, you may wish to make a point about the discipline-specific content.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Assessment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The effectiveness of this lesson will be determined by how critically students read maps in future weeks.\par}
